---
ARTICLE
summary:      Two independent papers published in 2016-2017 proved that key fairness metrics — calibration, equalised odds, and demographic parity — cannot all be satisfied simultaneously except in trivial cases. Chouldechova showed that calibration and equal false positive/negative rates are mutually exclusive when base rates differ. Kleinberg, Mullainathan, and Raghavan proved a broader version showing three natural fairness conditions are incompatible.
claims:
  - Calibration and equalised odds cannot both be satisfied when base rates differ between groups
  - This incompatibility is a mathematical fact, not a limitation of any particular algorithm
  - The choice of which fairness metric to prioritise is therefore a normative decision, not a technical one
  - Satisfying all three conditions simultaneously is only possible when base rates are equal or prediction is perfect
evidence:     Formal mathematical proofs in both papers, independently verified by the research community
limitations:  The theorems apply to the specific formal definitions of these metrics. Approximate versions or alternative formalisations may permit partial compatibility.
methodology:  Mathematical proof by contradiction. Both papers construct formal impossibility results from the definitions of calibration and error rate parity.
---
NOTES
The impossibility theorem is the most important theoretical result in algorithmic fairness. It reframes fairness from a technical optimisation problem to a value alignment problem. No amount of better data or better algorithms can resolve the tension — society must choose which type of fairness to prioritise in each context. This result directly explains why the ProPublica-Northpointe dispute was unresolvable: both sides were correct under their chosen metric.
